05841nam a22013575i 9780691224985DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20221990nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2020759417  a9780691224985  a(DE-B1597)576624  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aDS731.M35 7aHIS0080002bisacsh1 aCrossley, Pamela Kyle, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOrphan Warriors :bThree Manchu Generations and the End of the Qing World /cPamela Kyle Crossley. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©1990  a1 online resource (324 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tConventions -- tIntroduction -- tPart One -- tPart Two -- tConclusion -- tSource Abbreviations -- tNotes -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the mid-1600s, Manchu bannermen spearheaded the military force that conquered China and founded the Qing Empire, which endured until 1912. By the end of the Taiping War in 1864, however, the descendants of these conquering people were coming to terms with a loss of legal definition, an ever-steeper decline in living standards, and a sense of abandonment by the Qing court. Focusing on three generations of a Manchu family (from 1750 to the 1930s), Orphan Warriors is the first attempt to understand the social and cultural life of the bannermen within the context of the decay of the Qing regime. The book reveals that the Manchus were not "sinicized," but that they were growing in consciousness of their separate ethnicity in response to changes in their own position and in Chinese attitudes toward them. Pamela Kyle Crossley's treatment of the Suwan Guwalgiya family of Hangzhou is hinged upon Jinliang (1878-1962), who was viewed at various times as a progressive reformer, a promising scholar, a bureaucratic hack, a traitor, and a relic. The author sees reflected in the ambiguities of his persona much of the plight of other Manchus as they were transformed from a conquering caste to an ethnic minority. Throughout Crossley explores the relationships between cultural decline and cultural survival, polity and identity, ethnicity and the disintegration of empires, all of which frame much of our understanding of the origins of the modern world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aManchusxSocial life and customs. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh  aAlbazinians.  aAnhui.  aAnnam.  aBabojab.  aBogue.  aBritain.  aBuddhism.  aCanton (Guangzhou).  aChangxi.  aChen Tianhua.  aDai Xi.  aDong Fuxiang.  aEight Trigrams Rebellion.  aEnming.  aFujian.  aGelao hui.  aGong Zizhen.  aGuan Tianpei.  aGuanyin.  aGuizhou.  aHangzhou.  aHeilongjiang (province).  aHualianbu.  aHulun federation.  aJiangxi.  aJingshan diary.  aJohnston, Reginald.  aKang Youwei.  aKorea and Koreans.  aKuoputongwu.  aLi Hongzhang.  aLiang Qichao.  aManchukuo.  aManwen xuexiao.  aMing dynasty.  aMongolian banners.  aNanjing.  aNew Army.  aadoption.  abanishment.  ablack markets.  achildren.  aclans.  acorruption.  adivination.  aeducation.  aexaminations.  aforeign aid and advisors.  afuxiaoqi canling.  agenealogy.  ahanjian.  ahomelessness.  aidentity.  aimperial archives.  aindemnities.  airregulars.  amagistracy.  amercenaries.  aopium addiction.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Gap Yearsz978311078423740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978069122498540uhttps://ww